    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-11-30T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-11-30T22:00:00-05:00" n="47"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d47">
                <head>47. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d47fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 310.2/11–3058. Secret; Priority.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-11-30T21:00:00-06:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 30, 1958—9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_DULTE1">Dulte</gloss> 2. Following are action items from
                    Secretary’s conversation with President today:</p>
                <p>[Here follows paragraph 1 concerning Germany.]</p>
                <p>2. Re Hungary in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>, US will at appropriate time
                    introduce resolution on rejection credentials. In connection with the resolution
                    US would note provisions of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Charter on
                    expulsion and suspension of members, and in the certainty of Soviet veto of
                    effort to expel or suspend Hungary, would frankly set out to make “new law” in
                    the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> by rejection present Hungarian
                    Delegation’s credentials on the ground of flagrant and persistent violation of
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> resolutions. US will not lobby in support
                    of such resolution. Timing of its introduction is technical matter depending on
                    status of credentials matter; if for example in credentials committee or
                    elsewhere it is proposed to accept <pb facs="0113" n="83" xml:id="pg_83"/>
                    Hungarian credentials, US would counter with its proposal for rejection.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d47fn2">Tedul 5 to San Francisco, December 3, requested
                        clarification of the instructions not to “lobby” for a resolution rejecting
                        the Hungarian credentials. (<hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., 310.2/12–358)
                        Telegram 510 to <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, also December 3,
                        informed <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> of <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s and Dulles’ decision, noted
                        that the Department was seeking clarification of the instructions, and
                        stated that Dulles wanted <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> to
                        consult with Senators <persName corresp="#p_MMJ1">Mansfield</persName> and
                        Hickenlooper to gain their support for the U.S. efforts. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >Ibid</hi>.)</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows paragraph 3 concerning an unrelated subject.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName>Dulles</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
